## Response & Complexity Legend

**Response category** (per the assessment package definitions):
Native · Configuration · Custom Development · Third-Party · Not Supported

**Complexity / effort:** Low (<40h) · Medium (40–200h) · High (>200h) · Major Enhancement (product development / major extension)

**Split rating (added June 11, 2026):** where the portal scope expansion applies, complexity is shown as **Epic:** (Connect Care config/build effort) **· Portal:** (custom portal build effort). This keeps the Epic-facing response clean while still tracking total solution effort. Portal-side ratings assume a shared portal platform (authentication, site registry, notification engine, batch sync) built once and amortized across rows.

**Architecture premise carried from the Gap Assessment:** internal users (PVD, 13 regional depots, Public Health sites) operate on Connect Care HyperDrive directly; community pharmacies and physician clinics reach Willow through a **custom web portal** that authenticates against Epic provider-portal credentials and submits orders via **GHX XML batch import (Batch Scheduler template 48016)** as the primary path, with Interconnect/FHIR reserved for status reads and urgent orders. Vaccines are assumed to be built as **medications** (improving the FHIR read/catalog surface). *(Portal scope expanded June 11, 2026 — see portal scope expansion premise below.)*

**Location-model confirmation (June 11, 2026):** it is confirmed that Willow Inventory locations require **no linkage to Epic Departments or Facilities**. Community pharmacy, physician, and any external non-Epic location can be created as inventory locations with no real limitations. The multi-organization inventory model gap is **resolved** and removed from the Gap Assessment; remaining work is security/reporting configuration, not architecture.

**Scaling assumption (updated June 9, 2026):** the existing Connect Care instance is provisioned for ~100,000 users; adding the VIMS user population (≈5,000 named / 500–1,000 concurrent per AD-07) is treated as a marginal load that **does not impact clinical operations**. Raw infrastructure capacity is therefore **no longer treated as an open risk**. The remaining throughput consideration is narrower: the batch-import/portal path and any peak external ordering surge, not the Epic instance itself.

**External on-hand capture premise (added June 11, 2026):** community providers (pharmacies, physician clinics) report current on-hand inventory **through the portal**, and the portal back end **re-purposes Willow's ADS (medication cabinet) load/unload interface** to post those counts as HL7 ZPM messages against the corresponding external Willow inventory locations. Per the Pharmacy Inventory Management Guide ("Turn on Automatic Inventory Tracking for ADS Pharmacies," pp. 84–86): the system auto-creates inventory locations, items, and balances from inbound messages; balances are updated from ZPM-11 (delta) / ZPM-16 (total count); par/optimum/maximum levels are maintained from ZPM-22/ZPM-23. Consequences:

- External on-hand becomes **native Willow balance data** — Cogito/SlicerDicer report external sites like internal ones; no separate external-visibility data store.
- The **portal is the single aggregation point**: one consolidated inbound interface, not ~1,500 point feeds from heterogeneous pharmacy systems. Physician clinics without dispensing software are covered by manual portal counts.
- Pairing with **inventory hold locations** (PIM Guide pp. 31–32) — each depot designated as hold location for its sites — means a site's receipt-time "load" message auto-transfers stock depot→site, providing **native receipt confirmation** (closes the A4 post-ship gap created by imported requests closing on ship, p. 156).
- Count messages (ZPM-16 total-in-pocket semantics) double as **remote cycle counts**, replacing the missing external reconciliation path.

⚠ Confirm with Epic: (a) supportability/licensing of the ADS load/unload interface with a **non-ADS message source** (portal back end emulating a cabinet); (b) **lot/expiry granularity** carried in ZPM messages — gates the B2/D3/A7/D5 upgrades; (c) whether hold-location auto-transfer behaviour applies when the "ADS" is an emulated external location.

**Portal scope expansion (added June 11, 2026):** the custom web portal is elevated from external order entry + on-hand capture to the **front-end application for the larger Epic gaps at all non-Epic locations**. The portal syncs with Willow through the already-defined paths — GHX XML batch import (template 48016), the ADS ZPM feed, Interconnect/FHIR reads, and Cogito extracts — and accepts **batch file uploads** (e.g., from pharmacy dispensing systems) where direct interfaces are impractical. The portal is also the **single notification application for non-Epic inventory locations**: shipment, low-stock, near-expiry, recall, and account-event notifications to external sites are issued from the portal's notification engine, not from Epic. Functions absorbed by the portal:

- **Tier-based ordering rules & product-list eligibility** (A2) — enforced at portal order entry.
- **Order approval queueing** (C2) — external orders held in the portal for depot/program review *before* batch import; Willow only ever receives approved orders.
- **Variance thresholds & exception justification** (C5/C6) — threshold checks against Willow pars/on-hand at order entry; reason codes captured in the portal and preserved for audit.
- **Recall execution** (A7/D5) — multi-site notification, acknowledgement tracking, freeze-at-order-entry (recalled lots blocked from ordering), return tracking, completion reporting. Identification stays native in Cogito.
- **Redistribution pull-back** (A8) — pull-back instructions and return tracking issued through the portal.
- **Guided external returns & cold-chain incident capture** (A6/B8) — portal forms for external sites; results posted to Willow via the established feeds.
- **Post-ship / receipt status** (C3) — the portal owns provider-facing status after import, covering the imported-requests-close-on-ship limitation (PIM Guide p. 156).

Net effect: Epic-side custom development shrinks materially — most "Custom Development" rows become Epic configuration plus a portal module — and the recall gap drops from Major Enhancement to a portal build. The trade is **concentration risk**: one custom application now carries many requirements (see new Section 5 gap). ⚠ Confirm with Epic: outbound event/extract mechanism (push vs scheduled extract vs Interconnect polling) to feed the portal notification engine.

